# AKIS backend — ENV TEMPLATE (variable NAMES only; NEVER commit real values).
#
# Usage:
#   cp backend/.env.example backend/.env   # then fill the ones you need
#   export AKIS_ENV_FILE=backend/.env       # point the loader at your file
#   pnpm --filter @akis/backend dev
# Notes:
#   • A real shell env var ALWAYS wins over the file (the loader never overrides it).
#   • With NO provider key set, AKIS runs on the deterministic MOCK provider
#     (a fully working keyless demo — no real API calls).
#   • "REQUIRED" below means required only for that capability (real builds / prod / OAuth / DB).

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 1) AI PROVIDER  — set ONE key to run REAL builds (otherwise mock). [most important]
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Optional: force a provider/model. If unset, AKIS auto-detects from whichever key is present.
AI_PROVIDER=                 # anthropic | openai | openrouter | google | mock
AI_MODEL=                    # optional single model id; else the provider catalog default

# Set the key for the provider you use (the per-provider var is preferred):
ANTHROPIC_API_KEY=           # ← recommended (AKIS is Claude-first by default)
OPENAI_API_KEY=
OPENROUTER_API_KEY=
GEMINI_API_KEY=              # Google Gemini  (GOOGLE_API_KEY is an accepted alias)
GOOGLE_API_KEY=
AI_API_KEY=                  # generic fallback — ONLY used when AI_PROVIDER is set explicitly above

# Optional base-URL overrides (else per-provider catalog defaults):
ANTHROPIC_BASE_URL=
OPENAI_BASE_URL=
OPENROUTER_BASE_URL=
GOOGLE_BASE_URL=

# Encrypted KeyStore — only for the Settings-UI "save key" path (not for env-only keys):
AI_KEY_ENCRYPTION_KEY=             # 32-byte master key: 64 hex chars OR base64 of 32 bytes
AI_KEY_ENCRYPTION_KEY_VERSION=v1
# AI_KEY_STORE_PATH=               # default ~/.config/akis/keys.json — keep it OUTSIDE any git repo

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 2) SERVER
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
PORT=3000
HOST=127.0.0.1               # bind address. Default 127.0.0.1 (loopback) for local dev.
                             # IN A CONTAINER set HOST=0.0.0.0 or the published port is
                             # unreachable (the docker-compose stack sets this for you).
NODE_ENV=development         # development | production  (prod fails closed without AUTH_JWT_SECRET)
PUBLIC_BASE_URL=             # browser-facing origin. REQUIRED for OAuth + cross-site cookies.
                             # dev → the frontend, e.g. http://localhost:5173
                             # bundled self-host → the app origin, e.g. http://localhost:3000

# Self-host: serve the built frontend (frontend/dist) AND the API on ONE port.
# 1/true → the backend also serves the SPA via @fastify/static; the Docker image
# sets this so `docker compose up` gives you the whole app on http://localhost:3000.
# Leave blank in split dev (Vite on 5173 proxies the API).
SERVE_STATIC=                # 1 → serve frontend/dist alongside the API (bundled self-host)

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 3) AUTH  (JWT-in-cookie)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
AUTH_JWT_SECRET=             # REQUIRED in production (HS256 signing secret); dev uses an ephemeral key.
                             # An EMPTY value in production fails closed. The docker-compose stack
                             # ships an INSECURE default so the keyless demo boots — override it
                             # (AUTH_JWT_SECRET=$(openssl rand -hex 32)) for any real use.
AUTH_COOKIE_NAME=akis_session
AUTH_COOKIE_MAXAGE=604800    # seconds (604800 = 7 days)
AUTH_COOKIE_SECURE=false     # true in production (HTTPS)
AUTH_COOKIE_SAMESITE=lax     # lax | strict | none   (none forces Secure)
AUTH_COOKIE_DOMAIN=          # optional, e.g. .yourdomain.com to share the cookie across subdomains

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 4) OAuth  (optional — a button appears only when a provider's id AND secret are both set)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
GITHUB_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID=
GITHUB_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET=
GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_ID=
GOOGLE_OAUTH_CLIENT_SECRET=

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 5) Persistence / self-host  (optional — in-memory when unset; uses `pg`)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# Set DATABASE_URL to a Postgres DSN to ACTIVATE persistence: users + sessions +
# workflows then survive restarts. Unset → fast in-memory mode (great for the demo).
# The bundled docker-compose stack wires this automatically to its `db` service:
DATABASE_URL=                # e.g. postgres://user:pass@host:5432/akis
                             # docker-compose default → postgres://akis:akis@db:5432/akis
# Note: the vector / RAG knowledge index is NOT persisted yet — it re-builds on
# restart from your configured sources (documented deferral; see docs/SELF_HOSTING.md).

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 6) Feature flags / runtime  (all optional; safe defaults shown — leave blank to disable)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
AKIS_RAG=                    # 1/true → embedded RAG (knowledge retrieval + retrieve_knowledge tool). default OFF
AKIS_EMBEDDING_MODEL=        # OpenAI embedding model when a real embedder is enabled (see below).
                             # default text-embedding-3-small (dim 1536); also text-embedding-3-large (3072).
                             # ─── Real semantic embeddings (P2-RAG-1) ────────────────────────────────
                             # RAG retrieval uses an OFFLINE, deterministic embedder by default (no key,
                             # works out of the box, reproducible golden eval). To turn on REAL semantic
                             # embeddings, just set OPENAI_API_KEY (above) — or save an OpenAI key in the
                             # Settings UI; the SAME key the chat provider uses. The moment that key
                             # resolves AND NODE_ENV is not 'test', AKIS uses OpenAI's embeddings endpoint
                             # (text-embedding-3-small). No key ⇒ stays on the offline default (zero change).
AKIS_REAL_TESTS=             # 1/true → REAL verification: Trace BOOTS the produced app + HTTP-probes the running server (boot-smoke, no browser). Needs pnpm in the image for node-service apps. Set AKIS_ALLOW_MOCK=0 too (mock shadows it). default = mock
AKIS_ALLOW_MOCK=             # 1/true → keyless demo: deterministic mock provider + demo verify.
                             # FALLBACK, not a force — auto-disabled once a real provider key is set
                             # (the key wins). The docker-compose stack defaults this to 1 so a bare
                             # `docker compose up` runs a working demo with no key.
AKIS_DEMO_VERIFY=            # 1/true → mock test runner passes so a run reaches done WITHOUT real browsers
AKIS_ALLOW_DEMO_IN_PROD=     # 1/true → ACKNOWLEDGE a demo boot in production. A demo flag
                             # (AKIS_ALLOW_MOCK / AKIS_DEMO_VERIFY) FAKES verification, so under
                             # NODE_ENV=production the backend REFUSES to boot on a demo flag unless
                             # this is set. /health then reports mode:"demo" (the UI shows a badge).
                             # The docker-compose demo stack sets this to 1; clear it (and the demo
                             # flags) for a real production deployment. default unset (fail-closed in prod)
AKIS_WORKSPACES_DIR=         # where generated apps run/preview; default ~/.akis/workspaces.
                             # AKIS MANAGES this dir: on boot it reclaims orphaned workspaces left
                             # by a hard kill. Only entries it created (named <id>-<12-hex>) are
                             # removed, so pointing this at a populated dir won't wipe your files —
                             # but give AKIS its OWN directory anyway. default ~/.akis/workspaces
AKIS_PREVIEW_PROBE_ATTEMPTS= # max readiness-probe attempts (×250ms) before a preview boot is
                             # declared failed; raise for slow installs/builds. default 60 (~15s)

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 7) Real GitHub push (P1-CORE-2)  — OPT-IN; default is the in-memory mock adapter
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# When BOTH of these are set, a verified build's confirmPush opens (or updates) a REAL
# pull request on the target repo — branch + commit + PR via the GitHub REST API. The
# push is STILL gated: it runs only after all 4 structural gates pass (spec approval →
# no pre-approval code → real ≥1-test verification → digest-bound ApprovedPush). Leave
# EITHER blank → the mock adapter (no network). Under NODE_ENV=test the mock is ALWAYS
# used (tests/CI never push). The token is sent as a Bearer credential and is NEVER
# logged or returned in any response/event/error.
AKIS_GITHUB_PUSH_TOKEN=      # fine-grained PAT with `Contents`+`Pull requests` write on the
                             # target repo (or a GitHub App installation token). Required to enable.
AKIS_GITHUB_PUSH_REPO=       # "owner/name" of the target repo (e.g. me/my-app). Required to enable.
                             # May also be split: set AKIS_GITHUB_PUSH_OWNER + AKIS_GITHUB_PUSH_REPO=name.
AKIS_GITHUB_PUSH_OWNER=      # optional owner half when AKIS_GITHUB_PUSH_REPO holds only the name
AKIS_GITHUB_PUSH_BASE=       # optional base branch to open the PR against; default = repo default branch
AKIS_GITHUB_PUSH_API_BASE=   # optional GitHub Enterprise API base; default https://api.github.com
# NOTE: these are SEPARATE from the RAG reader's AKIS_GITHUB_TOKEN/REPO so push and
# knowledge-ingest can target different repos / use different-scoped tokens.

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# 8) Password-reset email (P5-OPS-1)  — OPT-IN; default is dev-echo (no email)
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# By DEFAULT (these unset) AKIS does NOT send email: in DEV the /auth/forgot-password
# response echoes the reset link so the flow is usable; in production no link is surfaced.
# Set AKIS_MAIL_FROM plus EITHER AKIS_SMTP_URL or the discrete host/port/user/pass below to
# deliver the reset LINK by email instead. The moment a mailer is configured the dev-echo is
# SUPPRESSED (the link goes by email, not in the HTTP response). The enumeration-safe
# "If that email has an account…" response is unchanged whether or not mail was sent, and
# the reset token/link is NEVER logged. Mailer is ALWAYS a no-op under NODE_ENV=test.
AKIS_MAIL_FROM=              # REQUIRED to enable. From address, e.g. "AKIS <noreply@you.dev>"
AKIS_SMTP_URL=              # one-line relay: smtp://user:pass@host:587 or smtps://user:pass@host:465
                            #   (smtps ⇒ implicit TLS). OR use the discrete vars below instead:
AKIS_SMTP_HOST=             # SMTP relay host (used when AKIS_SMTP_URL is unset)
AKIS_SMTP_PORT=587          # 465 ⇒ implicit TLS; 587/25 ⇒ plaintext submission
AKIS_SMTP_USER=             # optional SMTP auth username (AUTH LOGIN)
AKIS_SMTP_PASS=             # optional SMTP auth password — sent only in the AUTH exchange; never logged
AKIS_SMTP_SECURE=           # 1/true ⇒ force implicit TLS regardless of port (else inferred from 465)
# NOTE: the emailed link uses PUBLIC_BASE_URL (section 2) as its origin so it is clickable;
# without PUBLIC_BASE_URL the link is a relative path. STARTTLS is not implemented — for a
# remote relay use an implicit-TLS (smtps / 465) submission endpoint.

# ── Build Passport signing key (optional) ──────────────────────────────────
# On a verified build AKIS produces a durable, Ed25519-signed Build Passport — a portable,
# offline-verifiable proof of "passed N real tests behind the gates" — read at
# GET /sessions/:id/passport. Set AKIS_PASSPORT_PRIVATE_KEY to an Ed25519 PKCS#8 PEM for a
# STABLE operator-owned signing key (its published public key never changes). When unset, a
# clearly-DEV keypair is generated and persisted at AKIS_PASSPORT_KEY_PATH (default
# ~/.config/akis/passport.json, mode 0600) so the public key survives restarts. The private
# key is held only in memory and is NEVER logged or returned (only the public key is exposed).
AKIS_PASSPORT_PRIVATE_KEY=  # Ed25519 PKCS#8 PEM for a stable, operator-owned signer (else a DEV key is used)
AKIS_PASSPORT_KEY_PATH=     # where the generated DEV key persists (default ~/.config/akis/passport.json)

# AKIS_ENV_FILE is the POINTER to this file — set it in your SHELL, not inside the file:
#   export AKIS_ENV_FILE=backend/.env
